title: Grateful Dead Live at Robert F. Kennedy Stadium on 1994-07-16
lineage: AMS ST250 (FOB, ambisonic) > Modified Sony D10 pro2 > DAT > Tascam CDR 700 > EAC (secure) > mkwACT > SHN
description: Cold Rain & Snow, Picasso Moon, Lazy River Road, El Paso, If The Shoe Fits, Ramble on Rose, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Loose Lucy, Promised Land China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Samba In The Rain, Estimated Prophet-> Crazy Fingers-> Drums-> Space-> The Last Time-> Stella Blue-> One More Saturday Night, E Liberty

reviews.review_text: wish I stayed I lost my face at this show & left..hahahaha. the zombies were out.. ever try to leave during the show? we couldnt get out it seemed like it took an hour to get out of there....so anyway.. So cool the moon was out real nice & everybody was flippin out for picassoo moon. Last thing i remember was Ramble on rose. Didnt really remember much musically from this show . sounds great on this recording though. worth a listen.
My first show This was my first show. I didn't know much abou the Dead's music at the time, and now I am amazed that I witnessed such a great setlist! The first day of the rest of my life.
1st and only show I was trippin' so hard I barely remember the show.  Had a great time though, lucky I got to see them.  Always wanted a copy of this show.  Sound quality A-.

My Last Dead Show This was the last time I got to see Jerry with the Dead. I had been going to shows since Hartford back in 1980 and had seen the Dead around 60 or so times since then. After Jerry died, I caught The Other Ones a couple of times at SPAC, but it just wasn't the same. Eventually kids and job commitments caught up with me and I havn't been to see the rest of the boys since 1998. I remember Traffic opened the show and played a greatest hits set that was pretty good. The Dead were just 'ok' in my opinion, but I had a great time as always (excluding the Chapel Hill show in '93). Nothing spectacular here, but at lease I got to hear Stella Blue one last time. "Dust off those rusty strings just one more time,Gonna make them shine" Goodnight Jer. 3 stars just 'cause. Aiko-Aiko!

Dad's first show Took my dad and his buddy to this show. What a blast! They said they never had so much fun sitting in traffic as they did that day. We made it just in time for the opening notes of Cold Rain and Snow. My dad and his friend decided to go for a little adventure and made their way to the front of the stage? I think it was the Jack Daniels talking. I believe they had more fun then I did. Half decent show.

last show I remember having the same thought I had in 76' after my first show, "I better see this band again before they are no longer together" I'm glad they gave me another 18yrs of travel, fellowship and vibes  for a lifetime. I went to both nights,CR&S a favorite opener was not as prominent as usual. Out of both nights this one was better, not much into Vince but can't be too picky. Stella Blue has always been my favorite, Liberty stuck in my head for many months afterwards, Traffic was a good polished crowd pleasing set ,but da boys were better, still performing the best they could, over & over again. Miss ya Jer!

decent show in d.c not as good as earlier RFK shows like 7-12-1990 or 6-20-1992
but still worth a listen sound quality is Ok for aud .  stella blue
is note worthy  version for 1994

Above Average for 1994 Brilliant Crazy Fingers
VERY good for an audience.

Very mediocre Saw both DC shows that summer.  Traffic was the better band both nights. Not that the Dead were awful ala 8/3 at Giants Stadium, but there wasn't a ton of energy.  Just not the band I first heard in 1970, first saw in 1974, and that was [and remains] such a huge part of my life.  Anyway, decent background music at work, but just not something that's going to make you sit up and take notice.

My first Dead showTitle: A Birthday with the Dead – My Most Mind-Blowing Grateful Dead Experience The night before my 19th birthday, I stood in a swirling sea of tie-dye, waiting for the Grateful Dead. As Jerry Garcia and the band took the stage, time melted away. The music was alive, a force that pulled us into another dimension. “Eyes of the World” stretched on, Garcia’s solos weaving magic through the air. The energy was electric, the crowd moving as one.

The next night, on my 19th birthday, the band somehow topped it. “Scarlet Begonias” bled into “Fire on the Mountain,” and the encore, “Ripple,” felt like a personal gift. Every note, every moment, was transcendent. I wasn’t just at a concert—I was part of something bigger, something infinite. Two nights, one band, and a lifetime of memories. Some shows you see. Others, you live. This one? It was pure magic.
